00:00:01,110 --> 00:00:30,121
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:32,093 --> 00:00:39,963
So we're on number eight now of our perfections, our parami, those that take us to the other shore.

3
00:00:41,506 --> 00:00:49,156
It's resolution, adhitana, A-D-H-I-T-T-H-A-N-A, just in case you want to know.

4
00:00:50,579 --> 00:00:57,088
Tana means sort of position or place, your standing ground, and Adi just reinforces it.

5
00:00:57,945 --> 00:01:24,594
resolute resolution enormous resolve this is mirrored in the Buddha's life just before he became fully liberated you remember the story he left home finding the household life had become empty because of this problem of meaninglessness

6
00:01:26,430 --> 00:01:53,147
would have been expressed in those days as constant rebirth see constantly be having to come back and do the same thing all over again the same thing slightly different story but always you know being born growing up going old and dying and that constant constant thing is reincarnation so

7
00:01:55,405 --> 00:02:07,701
He then went out to try and find an answer to this end of suffering, as he would call it, something hard to bear, unsatisfactoriness, a fundamental unsatisfactoriness.

8
00:02:07,721 --> 00:02:14,891
And he tried all that business of developing absorption states, for they would disappear inside.

9
00:02:15,473 --> 00:02:18,256
And he tried self-mortification, and it just got very thin.

10
00:02:19,657 --> 00:02:23,082
And eventually he had that inspiration coming from childhood,

11
00:02:23,586 --> 00:02:48,328
the way that child gets wrapped into something and yet has that curiosity so that was his inspiration and he went to sit under this tree what we now call the Bodhi tree, the fig tree the religious fig tree and he made a determination either to crack this problem or to die

12
00:02:48,611 --> 00:03:14,299
that was the great determination and it took him six hours so it's mirrored in his life as that moment when he'd come to an end and he thought well either this is it or what's the point he was going to sit there until he dropped dead so

13
00:03:15,055 --> 00:03:42,766
this comes as one of the great virtues and you have to make a distinction between an intention and the intentioned intention the English word has this double meaning of meaning a wish I have an intention to go and I intended to do it meaning that you actually made an act of will so that's why

14
00:03:43,776 --> 00:03:50,288
We always make a distinction between the desire that arises and the empowerment of that desire.

15
00:03:50,328 --> 00:03:53,132
These are two moments, see, two moments.

16
00:03:54,413 --> 00:04:02,848
So even in simple things like, you know, a cup of tea, it comes up as a desire and nothing happens until you empower it.

17
00:04:02,867 --> 00:04:07,776
Normally speaking, it's habitual, you know, we just go and do it.

18
00:04:08,870 --> 00:04:17,821
But what meditation, what our mindfulness should do, daily mindfulness, is to make us more and more aware of these little intentions that come.

19
00:04:20,564 --> 00:04:24,088
And then there's this power that goes into an intention.

20
00:04:24,588 --> 00:04:26,632
That's your will.

21
00:04:27,452 --> 00:04:31,538
And it's the will that takes something out of potential into actual.

22
00:04:33,300 --> 00:04:36,783
So long as it remains a desire in the mind, nothing's happened.

23
00:04:37,490 --> 00:04:43,456
But as soon as you empower it, something happens, either a train of thoughts or an action or speech.

24
00:04:44,057 --> 00:04:45,579
One of the things happens.

25
00:04:45,598 --> 00:04:47,661
And that's what we understand as a kama.

26
00:04:50,103 --> 00:04:54,829
And the important thing is to know that this is how we condition ourselves, right?

27
00:04:54,850 --> 00:04:58,413
Through these intentions.

28
00:04:58,434 --> 00:05:05,742
Now, when an intention becomes, instead of habitual, something that you consciously make a decision about, right?

29
00:05:06,682 --> 00:05:31,475
then you have to be resolute about that you have to really sort of contemplate why you want to do something and then you do it and of course there's always a little clause that stops you from going and taking it overboard except in exceptional circumstance or emergency

30
00:05:32,182 --> 00:05:36,387
So you might determine to climb a mountain, see that corner there, where's the hill.

31
00:05:38,151 --> 00:05:44,600
And as you get up and up and up, you might find that you're getting colder and colder and colder, you haven't put the right clothes on.

32
00:05:44,620 --> 00:05:47,285
So in which case you have to come down because there's good reason.

33
00:05:47,985 --> 00:05:55,677
But if you got up and up and you felt, well, I can't be bothered getting to the top, then that wouldn't be a wholesome reason.

34
00:05:55,697 --> 00:05:55,877
See?

35
00:05:57,180 --> 00:05:59,083
And slowly but surely by

36
00:05:59,552 --> 00:06:26,437
by not completing your resolutions for good reasons you undermine your resolve you undermine your ability to commit yourself you never finish anything you know these people who say they can't finish anything see so you have to you have to be quite clear when you make a resolution that's what you're going to do this comes about also when even inadvertently you say you're going to help somebody and then you decide you don't want to do it

37
00:06:27,228 --> 00:06:53,843
so you're undermining constantly your commitment in this case you're undermining your goodwill and the spiritual life to do that in the spiritual life is really undermining because if you say to yourself I'm going to sit here for six hours I'm going to sit here until I become fully enlightened or I'll drop dead or I die and you give up after half an hour that's bad news isn't it

38
00:06:54,615 --> 00:07:02,791
Having made a rational decision that you are going to sit here for 40 minutes, you see, try to keep it.

39
00:07:03,233 --> 00:07:08,324
Even if you're shifting and moving and doing all sorts of silly things, you keep to that resolve, you see.

40
00:07:08,343 --> 00:07:13,975
And then there's that lovely feeling of having completed your commitment, you see.

41
00:07:15,574 --> 00:07:24,024
I remember when I first started meditating in the Zen, you know, we were facing the wall, sitting on a bench, yeah?

42
00:07:24,264 --> 00:07:25,865
I wasn't sitting cross-legged.

43
00:07:25,886 --> 00:07:33,334
So it must have been, it wasn't very long I'd started, but the pain was excruciating in the knees and whatnot, you know, really quite painful.

44
00:07:34,115 --> 00:07:36,357
But I was determined not to move.

45
00:07:36,396 --> 00:07:39,060
I was absolutely, you know, Zen, you know?

46
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:41,362
You bang your head against the wall, that's what it's for.

47
00:07:41,783 --> 00:07:44,485
That's why you sit next to the wall.

48
00:07:44,505 --> 00:07:45,447
But I couldn't take it, you see.

49
00:07:45,932 --> 00:07:50,017
And just as I gave up, the bell went.

50
00:07:50,177 --> 00:07:51,880
Oh, I felt terrible.

51
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:55,444
Oh, never again, I said.

52
00:07:55,564 --> 00:07:58,088
Never again will I give up on a resolve.

53
00:07:58,129 --> 00:08:01,213
So, be careful.

54
00:08:05,838 --> 00:08:12,226
So, you know, when you hear of people trying to overcome certain...

55
